<p>86 The decline in the number of FBN arrests and seizures is
directly related to the increase in local and state enforcement
personnel. This thesis is supported by data from California where
statewide arrests soared while federal arrests remained stable.
Bureau of Criminal Statistics, California Dep't of Justice, Crime
in California (1956). See also A. LiNDESMITH, THE ADDICT AND THE
LAW 238 (1963). One commentator has suggested that except for the
years immediately after the passage of the Marihuana Tax Act,
when the Bureau wanted to concentrate on its newly acquired
enforcement field, the FBN arrest data show clearly its emphasis
on the hard narcotics. Mandel, Problems with Official Drug
Statistics, 21 STAN. L. REV. 991, 1019-20 (1969). </p>

